We just ran into something here that I wanted to document for future
people who might run into this.

Where I work we have our own implementation of java.security.Provider.
This implementation lives in a jar file that&#39;s signed by us and with
the JCE Code Signing thing. (I don&#39;t remember the details, I&#39;m not the
cryppie guy, but jarsigner -verify -certs -verbose shows that all the
files are signed by both certs)

I had a test that called a method that takes in a string and encrypts
it with a password using a substitution algorithm. The snippet:

        try
        {
            String provider = &quot;name.of.our.crypto.provider.class&quot;;
            Class providerClass = Class.forName(provider);

java.security.Security.addProvider((java.security.Provider)
providerClass.newInstance());
        }
        catch (Throwable t)
        {
            t.printStackTrace();
        }

        SecretKeySpec s = new SecretKeySpec(cipher, &quot;SUBSTITUTION&quot;);
        SubstAlgorithmParameters p = new SubstAlgorithmParameters();
        // we set some parameters for this algorithm

        try
        {
            Cipher c =
Cipher.getInstance(&quot;SUBSTITUTION&quot;,&quot;name.of.our.crypto.provider&quot;);


And it was puking on Cipher.getInstance saying that the file might not
have been signed. So we put in some simple debugging code:

            String provider = &quot;name.of.our.crypto.provider&quot;;
            Class providerClass = Class.forName(provider);
            Object[] signers = providerClass.getSigners();
            if (signers == null) {
                System.err.println(&quot;No signers!&quot;);
                signers = new Object[0];
            }
            System.err.println(&quot;Signer count for &quot;+provider+&quot;:
&quot;+signers.length);

And sure enough, signers was null and &quot;No signers!&quot; would appear.

The same block of code, and all of our tests, run fine both naturally
and in the textui runner.

So... there is some funky classloader thing going on here that I don&#39;t
understand. I just wanted to see if this was known (I haven&#39;t found
anything anywhere else about signed jar files yet) and what people
thought.

Thanks for your time!

